            <p>As you can see, some of the modern English modals come from the same Old English verb in its past and present forms: so the verb 
                <em>sculan</em> is the basis of modern English <em>shall</em> (from <em>sceal</em>) <strong>and</strong> <em>should</em> (from 
                <em>scolde</em>). </p>
            <h3>Preterite Present Verbs</h3>
                <p>As you might remember from the <a class="darkorange-text"
                href="irregular.html">Irregular Verbs</a> module, <em>willan</em> is an irregular verb, but most of the rest of the Old English 
                modal auxiliaries are so-called preterite-present verbs, which are essentially 
                strong verbs that have had their present and past forms swapped, and which take weak verb endings in the past. This sounds complicated
                but in practice they are easy to recognise because we have in most cases taken both the past and present forms into modern English: 
                can / could, for example, and may / might. See the sentences below: '<em>Hwæt sceal ic don? - What shall/should I do?</em>' 
                and '<em>Eal folc sceolde fæsten ðri dagas - All folk should fast for three days</em>': the modal should be recognisable in both cases.
            </p>
