            <h3>Using Modal Verbs</h3>
            <p>In simple constructions modal auxiliaries are followed by a verb in the infinitive (as in modern English 'I should eat/leave/run').
                To recap, the <strong>infinitive</strong> is the base form of a verb, which ends in <strong>-an</strong> in Old English. Modal auxiliary + 
                infinitive constructions such as '<em>Ic cann rune writan - I can write runes</em>' or '<em>Heo mæg me gehælan - She may heal me'</em> behave in 
                exactly the same way as in modern English: the modal verb is followed by the main verb in the infinitive.
